However, access to safe abortion services remains legally restricted across the country. In 2015, of the estimated 20 million pregnancies across the country, one million had reportedly induced abortions, leading to an annual rate of 75 induced abortions per 1,000 women of reproductive age (15–49 years). Half (50%) of those procedures were unsafe. More accurate estimates are not readily available since induced abortions are illegal in almost all countries without exceptions for rape, incest, life endangerment, or severe fetal anomaly. According to the United States’ Central Intelligence Agency World Factbook, Tanzania has some of the lowest maternal mortality rates in eastern Africa, with an estimated maternal mortality ratio of 430 deaths per 100,000 live births. Given country-wide abortion restrictions, including an absolute ban and the introduction of mandatory hospitalization for up to five days before abortion services, for many couples, the only form of “birth control” is “compliance” with space-making. This “continuum of compliance,” entailing recurrent births to ensure adequate spacing, is the most common form of child-spacing in low-resource settings. It involves learning to tolerate perpetual stress and anxiety, thereby contributing to high rates of maternal mortality.
